1. General Principles
  Follow Shopify’s Liquid & Theme Development standards.
  Code should be readable, maintainable, and reusable.
  DRY principle: no copy-pasting; extract snippets/sections where needed.
  Use semantic HTML5 for better SEO & accessibility.
  Optimize for performance: fewer requests, lighter assets.
  Every feature should work without breaking the Online Store Editor (theme customizer).

2. Liquid (Shopify’s Template Language)
  Always wrap logic with default fallbacks:
  
   {{ product.title | default: "Product Name" }}
  Avoid complex logic in Liquid — push business logic to JSON schema settings or JS where possible.
  Use {% render %} instead of {% include %}
  Never hardcode strings — use locales (locales/en.default.json).
  Organize sections and snippets by purpose (naming convention: component-*, section-*, util-*).
  Keep schema JSON minimal and validated.



3. HTML & Accessibility
  Always use semantic tags (<header>, <main>, <article>, <footer>).
  Provide alt text for images.
  Ensure ARIA attributes where needed.
  Headings should follow a logical hierarchy (<h1> once per page, then <h2>, <h3>, etc.).
  All forms must have labels and clear error states.
  Test keyboard navigation.




4. CSS / SCSS / Styling
  Follow BEM (Block–Element–Modifier) naming convention:

	 .button {}
  .button__icon {}
  .button--primary {}
  Use CSS variables where possible for consistency (--color-text, --color-bg).
  Prefer TailwindCSS or utility classes
  No inline styles in Liquid/HTML.
  Minimize CSS file size → remove unused selectors.
  Use clamp() or calc() for responsive typography.



5. JavaScript
  Vanilla JS preferred; no jQuery at all.
  Organize scripts in modules/components.
  Defer or lazy-load JS where possible (defer, async).
  Avoid polluting global scope; wrap in IIFE or ES modules.
  Use data-attributes to bind logic instead of hardcoding IDs.
  All AJAX calls should use fetch API (avoid legacy XMLHttpRequest).
  Provide graceful fallbacks if JS is disabled.



6. Assets (Images, Fonts, SVGs)
  Use Shopify’s image filters for resizing/compression:
  
  	 {{ product.featured_image | image_url: width: 800 }}
  Prefer inline SVG for icons over PNG.
  Avoid uploading fonts > 100KB; use system fonts or variable fonts where possible.
  Enable lazy loading (loading="lazy") for non-critical images.
  Minify all assets (CSS, JS, SVG).




7. Performance & SEO
  Every page must have:
  <title> and <meta description>.
  Canonical URL.
  OpenGraph & Twitter card tags.
  JSON-LD structured data (Product, Breadcrumbs, Articles).


  Only one H1 per page.
  Avoid render-blocking resources.
  Use Shopify’s native sections everywhere for flexibility.

8. Project Structure & Version Control
  Keep theme organized:
  
   /assets
  /config
  /layout
  /locales
  /sections
  /snippets
  /templates
  Commit messages should follow Conventional Commits:
  
  
  feat: add sticky add-to-cart bar
  fix: resolve mobile menu alignment
  
  
  No commits with unminified libraries or debug logs.
  Always use .gitignore for node_modules, build cache, private keys.



9. Testing Before Commit
  Run Theme Check locally.
  Test across desktop, tablet, mobile.
  Test in multiple browsers (Chrome, Safari, Firefox, Edge).
  Verify Online Store Editor doesn’t break.
  Confirm no console errors in browser dev tools.



10. Pull Request Guidelines
  PR must reference related issues/tickets.
  PR description must include:
  What has changed.
  How it was tested (screenshots or screen recording if possible).
  Checklist: lint passed, a11y checked, Lighthouse score OK.
  
  
  At least 1 reviewer approval required.
  No direct commits to the main branch.

Liquid / JSON Files:
  Lowercase, hyphen-separated (section-name).
  Keep type prefix for clarity.
  Examples:
  section-product-card.liquid
  snippet-cart-icon.liquid
  template-product.json

CSS/JS:
  Hyphen-separated, scoped if component-specific.

  Examples:
    cart-drawer.js
    section-hero-banner.css
    theme-utils.js

Images / SVGs:
  Lowercase, hyphen-separated.
  Examples:
    logo-primary.svg
    bg-hero.webp

Metafields
  Since metafields are namespaced keys, naming consistency is critical.
    Namespace: lowercase, underscores only.

      Use project or feature domain (avoid custom if possible).
      Examples:
        seo.title_tag
        product_specs.weight
        algolia_filters.awg_size

    Keys: lowercase, underscores only.
      Be descriptive, avoid abbreviations unless common.
      Examples:
        product_specs.material
        product_specs.size_guide_url
        Settings.recommended_products_limit

    Rules:

      Keep namespace stable (don’t rename casually → breaks data).
      Group metafields logically by feature (seo, shipping, pricing).
      Always document new metafields in your repo (docs/metafields.md).



  Git Branches
    Clear branch naming is essential for CI/CD pipelines and PR reviews.
    Main Branches:
    main → production
    develop → staging
    Feature Branches:
    
     feature/<jira-ticket-id>-<short-description>
     Examples:
    
    
    feature/WR011-sticky-add-to-cart
    feature/WR012-pdp-image-zoom


  Bugfix Branches:

   fix/<jira-ticket-id>-<short-description>
   Examples:
  
    fix/WR011-mobile-menu-alignment
    fix/WR011-checkout-discount-code


  Hotfix Branches (urgent prod fixes):

   hotfix/<jira-ticket-id>-<short-description>
   Example:

    hotfix/WR011-payment-button-bug

  Commits
    Stick with Conventional Commits so changelogs are automated:
      feat: → new feature
      fix: → bug fix
      docs: → documentation
      style: → code style (no logic change)
      refactor: → restructuring
      test: → adding tests
      chore: → misc (deps, build tasks)

    Examples:
      feat: add hero banner section
      fix: resolve cart drawer loading bug
      chore: update Shopify CLI version
